The '''Oregon Equality Act''' is a law of the U.S. state of [[Oregon]] which prohibits discrimination based on [[sexual orientation]] and [[gender identity]] in employment, housing, public accommodations, and other categories. Enacted in 2007, it became effective in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lambdalegal.org/sites/default/files/publications/downloads/fs_oregon-equality-act_0.pdf|title=The Oregon Equality Act: Protection for lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender people|publisher=Lambda Legal|accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>
The act passed during the [[74th Oregon Legislative Assembly]]. Senate Bill 2<ref>[https://olis.leg.state.or.us/liz/2007R1/Measures/Overview/SB2 Senate Bill 2, 2007 Regular Session], Oregon Legislature</ref> was introduced on March 5, 2007 in the [[Oregon Senate]], where it was approved on March 21 in a 21–7 vote. The [[Oregon House of Representatives]] amended the bill and voted 35–25 to approve it on April 17. The Oregon Senate voted 19–7 on April 19 to approve the amended bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salem-news.com/articles/april192007/senate_bill2_41907.php|title=Oregon's Senate Bill 2, The Oregon Equality Act, Passes in Senate Concurrence Vote|date=April 19, 2007|publisher=Salem News}}</ref> Governor [[Ted Kulongoski]] signed it on May 9, 2007 along with the [[Oregon Family Fairness Act]], and it took effect on January 1, 2008.
